[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] Welcome to the documentation for the Crystal language.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] Crystal is a language for humans and computers.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] These materials help humans understand the language and its ecosystem.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] These instructions and courses help you get to know the language and how to use it.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] A collection of external resources to help you take the most of the language.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] The core documentation of the Crystal language, standard library, and tooling.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] Discover the ecosystem of Crystal libraries.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] Detailed examples for practical applications.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] Instructions on how to use the compiler and tools.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] Announcements about the language development.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] If you want to dive into the development of Crystal, these materials give some guidance.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] A guide on how to open issues and contribute code to the Crystal project.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] The RFC process provides a consistent and controlled path to discuss substantial changes in the Crystal project and form a community consensus.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] Our standards and expectations about working together as a community.
[src:crystal-lang/1-14-index] How we take the decisions that guide the language and its community.
[src:crystal-lang/compiled-language] Informally, a **compiled language** is a programming language that is usually implemented with a compiler rather than an interpreter.
[src:crystal-lang/compiled-language] Because any language can theoretically be either compiled or interpreted, the term lacks clarity: compilation and interpretation are properties of a programming language implementation, not of a programming language.
[src:crystal-lang/compiled-language] Some languages have both compilers and interpreters.
[src:crystal-lang/compiled-language] Furthermore, a single implementation can involve both a compiler and an interpreter.
[src:crystal-lang/compiled-language] For example, in some environments, source code is first compiled to an intermediate form (e.g., bytecode), which is then interpreted by an application virtual machine.
[src:crystal-lang/compiled-language] In other environments, a just-in-time compiler selectively compiles some code at runtime, blurring the distinction further.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] Work on the language began in June 2011, with the aim of merging the elegance and productivity of Ruby with the speed, efficiency, and type safety of a compiled language.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] Initially named *Joy*, it was quickly renamed to *Crystal*.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] The Crystal compiler was first written in Ruby, but later rewritten in Crystal, thus becoming self-hosting, as of November 2013.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] The first official version was released in June 2014.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] In July 2016, Crystal joined the TIOBE index.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] Although resembling the Ruby language in syntax, Crystal compiles to much more efficient native code using an LLVM backend, at the cost of precluding the dynamic aspects of Ruby.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] The advanced global type inference used by the Crystal compiler, combined with union types, gives it more the feel of a higher-level scripting language than many other comparable programming languages.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] It has automated garbage collection and offers a Boehm collector.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] Crystal possesses a macro system and supports generics as well as method and operator overloading.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] Its concurrency model is inspired by communicating sequential processes (CSP) and implements lightweight fibers and channels (for interfiber communication), inspired by Go.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] In 2020, it was reported that the infotainment units in vehicles produced by Nikola Corporation were written in Crystal.
[src:crystal-lang/crystal-programming-language] Much of the backend of the Kagi search engine is written with Crystal.
[src:crystal-lang/syntax-and-semantics-index] This is a formal specification of the Crystal language.
[src:crystal-lang/syntax-and-semantics-index] You can read this document from top to bottom, but it’s advisable to jump through sections because some concepts are interrelated and can’t be explained in isolation.
[src:crystal-lang/syntax-and-semantics-index] The Language Introduction tutorial offers a more focused learning experience for beginners.
[src:crystal-lang/syntax-and-semantics-index] In code examples, a comment starting with `# =>` shows the value of an expression.
[src:crystal-lang/syntax-and-semantics-index] A comment starting with `# :` shows the type of an expression.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:crystal-lang/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
